DURBAN - Residents indebted to eThekwini Municipality for municipal services will from February 1 this year have to submit supporting documents for a customer affordability assessment to be conducted.The municipality said it is now mandatory for it to undertake an affordability assessment for customers in debt who want to enter into a payment arrangement with the municipality.Head of revenue Lihle Ndzelu said in a report on the city’s website, that this is in compliance with Sections 57 and 58 of the Magistrate’s Court Act 32 of 1944.“The city will require proof of income and expenditure to consider the affordability of the consumer to pay their instalments,” said Ndzelu.According to the municipality, for the affordability assessment it would require that the customer either fill out a financial affordability form or a financial affordability affidavit.MORE ON THIS​Outrage over eThekwini metro police overtime bill as ‘doubling salaries’ is questionedKZN political parties appeal to the police for protection after another politician is killedThe city said the financial affordability form will be filled by a customer who has proof of income, while the financial affordability affidavit is for those who do not possess proof of income.Ndzelu said the city is sensitive to the fact that a customer may not singularly meet the required monthly instalments. In this instance, she said the city would accept joint household income and/or surety.The city said the customer affordability assessment must be accompanied by supporting documents.“Supporting documentation required includes certified copies of a customer’s ID and payslip.“The payslips, if it is a joint household income, and certified copies of ID’s of all contributors must be provided. A three-month bank statement, if the applicant is self-employed, as well as a letter of executorship/letter of authority of the occupier of the property if no executor is appointed is also required. “For juristic persons, the audited annual financial statement and the company signature authorisation letter is required,” said the city.THE MERCURY